David, was constrained by his clergy to sail into Brittany to avoid a deadly epidemic which then afflicted Wales. He carried his pall, the sign of metropolitan dignity‚ with him, and deposited it in the church of Dol‚ where it was lest. And hence the metropolitan title was lost to S. David's. But if so, the pall must then have belonged topar- ticular churches, and could not, as in later ages, have been a personal distinction. For no metropolitan within the Roman Obedience can now exercise his authority in a new province without a renewal of the pall. And the loss of the pall itself could not now deprive an archbishop of his title or prerogative, which might be so easily restored hy the grant of another. Perhaps the poverty of the ree, which other historiens allege as a reason, is more probable. The clergy of Dol are said to have claimed exemp- tion from the jurisdiction of their fonner Metropoli- tan the archbishop ol Toum, in right of the pall which had been brought to their church. And this claim was not finally settled till 1198 by Pope Inno- cent 111¹.
